  abstract = {Opioid transmission and dysregulated prefrontal cortex (PFC) activity$\backslash$nhave both been implicated in the inhibitory-control deficits associated$\backslash$nwith addiction and binge-type eating disorders. What remains unknown,$\backslash$nhowever, is whether endogenous opioid transmission within the PFC$\backslash$nmodulates inhibitory control. Here, we compared intra-PFC opioid$\backslash$nmanipulations with a monoamine manipulation (d-amphetamine), in two$\backslash$nsucrose-reinforced tasks: progressive ratio (PR), which assays the$\backslash$nmotivational value of an incentive, and differential reinforcement of$\backslash$nlow response rates (DRLs), a test of inhibitory control. Intra-PFC$\backslash$nmethylnaloxonium (M-NX, a limited diffusion opioid antagonist) was given$\backslash$nto rats in a `low-drive' condition (2-h food deprivation), and also$\backslash$nafter a motivational shift to a `high-drive' condition (18-h food$\backslash$ndeprivation). Intra-PFC DAMGO (D-\{[\}Ala2, N-MePhe4, Gly-ol]-enkephalin;$\backslash$na mu-opioid agonist) and d-amphetamine were also tested in both tasks,$\backslash$nunder the low-drive condition. Intra-PFC M-NX nearly eliminated$\backslash$nimpulsive action in DRL engendered by hunger, at a dose (1 mu g) that$\backslash$nsignificantly affected neither hunger-induced PR enhancement nor$\backslash$nhyperactivity. At a higher dose (3 mu g), M-NX eliminated impulsive$\backslash$naction and returned PR breakpoint to low-drive levels. Conversely,$\backslash$nintra-PFC DAMGO engendered `high-drive-like' effects: enhancement of PR$\backslash$nand impairment of DRL performance. Intra-PFC d-amphetamine failed to$\backslash$nproduce effects in either task. These results establish that endogenous$\backslash$nPFC opioid transmission is both necessary and sufficient for the$\backslash$nexpression of impulsive action in a high-arousal, high-drive appetitive$\backslash$nstate, and that PFC-based opioid systems enact functionally unique$\backslash$neffects on food impulsivity and motivation relative to PFC-based$\backslash$nmonoamine systems. Opioid antagonists may represent effective treatments$\backslash$nfor a range of psychiatric disorders with impulsivity features.},
